Let’s push this a step closer to what engines like Unreal Engine actually do—still simplified, but more interesting.

We’ll build a mini reflection system that can:
    Access properties by name
    Modify them
    Call functions by name
    Keep everything in a registry

Idea
    We create:
        A base Reflectable class
        Store:
            properties → name → pointer
            functions → name → callable

What this demonstrates
    Now you have:
        Dynamic property access
            p.set("health", 200);

        Dynamic function calls
            p.call("heal");

        String-driven behavior

What’s still missing (compared to real reflection)
    This is where real engines go further:
        Type system
            We hardcoded int
            Real systems support many types
        Arguments in functions
            Our functions take no parameters
            Real reflection supports full signatures
        Auto registration
            We manually register everything
            Unreal auto-generates metadata via macros
        Inheritance-aware metadata
            Real systems walk class hierarchies

Key insight (important)
    What you just built is basically:
        Reflection = metadata + lookup + indirection
    And engines like Unreal automate:
        metadata creation (macros + tools)
        safe access (type system)
        editor integration